      {
        "id": 278186,
        "name": "üëäüá∫üá∏üî•",
        "username": "Avitus",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/{size}/34172_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-10-28T02:53:04.748Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Alex7511\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"72506\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/edb3f5/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Alex7511:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>links to Signal Foundation‚Äôs 2018 tax return and labels this ‚ÄúBrian Acton Injected over $100m into Signal‚Äù. I‚Äôm only aware of a $50m ‚Äúloan‚Äù mentioned in <a href=\"https://signal.org/blog/signal-foundation/\">Signal &gt;&gt; Blog &gt;&gt; Signal Foundation</a>. Is there a writeup anywhere that can clarify just how much folks like Acton currently fund (and therefore presumably control) the Signal Foundation?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Signal has a <a href=\"https://signalfoundation.org/\">board</a> of 5 people that governs the Signal Foundation. Brian Acton is just one member on the board of 5. His loan, effectively just seed money, was initially $50M, but was increased to $105M within the first couple years of the Foundation‚Äôs existence.</p>\n<p>Acton has publicly stated many times that he helped start the Signal Foundation because he regretted selling WhatsApp to Facebook once it became clear Zuckerberg lied about maintaining the principles of privacy it was built around and would inevitably bastardize it with data collection and ads. That started coming to fruition in 2021 when the ToS changed to allow data sharing with Facebook.</p>\n<p>It‚Äôs odd that the 2018 Form 990 is a point of criticism when there has been a new Form 990 <a href=\"https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/816178565\">made available</a> every year since, though the defunding of the IRS during both Trump administrations has caused a delay in publishing updates.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Alex7511\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"72506\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/edb3f5/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Alex7511:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>how can it be that Signal was compelled to disclose data to a government only once in the last 4 years? It feels highly improbable.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>The bar to subpoena is still very high in the U.S. For how much longer it‚Äôll remain high given how things are rapidly devolving across the federal government, and certain state governments, is unknown.</p>\n<p>Currently, when Signal receives a subpoena, they challenge it in court. I believe they only post on the site when they lose a challenge. When they win, there‚Äôs nothing to post because they‚Äôre not disclosing the (very minimal) user data they collect.</p>",
